 UNICEF has called a ?crisis of gargantuan proportions?, an estimated 15 million children under the age of 18 have lost one or both of their parents to AIDS. This number is projected to rise over the coming decades, even where HIV prevalence peaks or subsides. During PhD research, a new study was conducted in urban Zimbabwe to test the speculation that orphanhood in adolescence could increase vulnerability to HIV infection, thereby fuelling the AIDS epidemic through a cycle of infection within families. It was found that half of all teenage girls in a high-density township of Harare had lost at least one parent and 15 per cent had lost both. Orphaned adolescent girls were at higher risk of HIV and Herpes simplex virus type 2 than their peers with both parents alive. Through the post-doctoral fellowship over the next 2 years, the researcher will acquire additional analytical skills to deepen and expand the PhD analysis. In particular, the research will explore the specific causal pathways of risk for adolescent orphans, and disseminate findings through publications and ?analysis to action? workshops in Zimbabwe, so that a tailored response can be designed to prevent HIV among this growing population of vulnerable young people.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>185273</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnic